segments.text: With the doctor, you paid 50 cents every two weeks per family, and that took care of all the medical services.
No, that wouldn't take care of the medicine.
They had to pay the drugs, too, you know.
Yeah, but the doctor, he'd get that 50 cents from each family.
That was understood among the Mexicans, too, you know, that when payday came, you got to pay that 50 cents for the doctor, so much for the drugs.
The bookkeeper would take that right off of their paycheck.
Who was the bookkeeper?
Theodore Walter.
Theodore Walter?
W-A-L-T-E-R. And was he at the commissary?
No, he did live over here on the...
When you come out here, the last house, you know, not the last house is on this side, where the road goes that way.
That goes to Cabot Ridge.
And he lived right behind those woods over there, down the road a little piece.
I see.
And he would come in every two weeks and fix the books, you know, and they'd go to 7-1 to go to town in the buggy and get the money, you know.
So they paid you and the Mexicans in cash?
Yeah, cash, yeah.
He'd go to that money, get the money that he would then pay off, you know, at the cumbersome, you know, or eat at Grandma's house.
Like I've been telling them, every two weeks he'd go to town to get the payroll, five, six hundred dollars, and nobody didn't rob him one time.
you know, all the time, all them years.
But I bet these days he couldn't do it in a horse and buggy.
He would get outside the city and somebody robbed him.
Oh, my gosh.
That is incredible.
That there were no robberies.
Yeah, not at all.
You know, the Mexicans all knew it.
You'd go to town every other week.
You didn't get that payroll file, $600.
So the Mexicans would go to Rockville to pick up their money?
No.
Walter...
the bookkeeper, he'd go down and get the money from the bank on the side of this and pay off that even out there at the commissary, you know, at the store, yeah, pay off, yeah.
And then would the Mexicans come into town to spend their money?
Yeah, they spent some, yeah.
I see.
Do you remember any, you know, anecdotal stories
you know, about the mines, anything that you, when you're just sitting down sometime and thinking about mining?
They like, the Mexicans like to drink a lot, you know.
They'd come home from town drunk off a hoop in the holland, you know.
What would they drink, Muslim?
Was it beer or whiskey?
I don't know.
They'd hoot from holland, they'd get too bad, then Grandma would, you know,
They called her mama, grandmother.
Grandma Vogel?
Uh-huh.
Called her mama.
She was brought to camp, you know, in the house.
She ran the camp then.
Uh-huh.
She owned the house.
Well, the mines too long, you know, they were hard too.
Did they like Grandma Vogel?
Yeah, they liked her.
She told them they used to behave, you know.
She'd tell them to behave, and they'd say, Mama, I'm sorry.
I'm not going to do it no more.
I'm not going to do it no more.
Next Saturday, come along and get drunk again.
But that's natural.
They do that these days, too.
Would you like to come and sit down here?
Oh, I want to do something first.
OK. Grandpa Vogel, he did that camp out there.
He put up a dance hall.
He figured it would have entertainment, you know?
Mm-hmm.
They had one dance, the first night they had a dance, they had a big fight and a bunch of men got cut up, you know.
He said if they couldn't behave themselves, they don't need no entertainment, so no more dances.
You had one dance at the dance hall?
Yeah, this one.
He tore down after all.
He said if they couldn't behave themselves, he didn't want that kind of doings, you know.
So he finally tore it down again.
They had a big two-story building there.
They call it the boarding house.
He had that dance hall built around here, and he could sit around it, you know, and dance in the middle.
Yeah, one day, the first night, a bunch of messengers got drunk, you know, they cut the university and used a knife and all that, you know.
Do you remember about what year this was?
I don't remember.
I guess I'm old enough to remember, but he said no more.
Yeah, you was too young those days.
Yeah, I was too young then.
I was born in 1900.
See, I'll be 77 years old in December 21st.
December 21st, 1900 when I was born.
That's a long time.
And I remember Grandpa died, I remember.
That was about what time?
I don't remember what year.
Grandpa, see, he fell.
They dig a shaft, you know, and he fell down there one day, you know.
He said, I guess, you know, and he died.
Grandpa did, yeah.
Grandpa Vogel.
Yes.
Do you remember the great flood of the early 1920s when Rockville inundated with all this rain?
I don't remember.
I don't believe.
In 1930, I guess it did.
Well, how did the Depression affect you?
Do you remember how the Depression affected the mines?
You mean 1930?
Right.
Well, they didn't have no more mines then.
The mines quit in 1917, the mines.
They didn't have no more mines then.
In 1917, the mines all quit out here.
All but one, a Spanish... A full 100-hour mine.
Dr. Sprott had a mine yet later on, but they, mines, 1930, mines was all equipped.
We lived out here over 19, we moved out here in 1919.
The mines were all played out by then.
No, they couldn't sell enough lignite then when they got that oil, you know.
In the end, they used lignite, and when they got the boomer, they started to gush it down on them.
Then they started using the oil and gas because they were cheaper, you know, and cleaner.
They quit using lignite, so they had to quit.
Now, now, oil is so hard, you know, they could use lignite to get, you know.
I go to A&M College.
Right.
Right.
And they quit, too, then, you know.
They said oil was cheaper, and they quit buying it.
So, Daddy said, you know, he was trying to...
If you go out to Henry, McCurtain's brown boy, you know, he might take you out and show you around, you know, if he got time.
Somebody, he wasn't here before, no.
No, that was Julio.
What?
That was Julio.
Somebody else, you know, said the brown boy took him out there and showed him around, you know.
See, he owns all that old rich amount.
He went for the railroad, so you might not catch him in town during the week.
Mostly on Sundays.
He's at home some days.
I don't know.
Well, I'll be here for a couple weeks.
You can find out.
If you go out there, his...
But that, we talk too much?
Oh, no, no.
I just wanted to get it back to the starting place.
I wanted you to tell me about the malaria of my... Oh.
Well, we told you we had to cut the doctor.
And we'd have malaria, fever.
Some of us in our family would too, Mexicans.
And we'd get the doctor to come out.
And everybody paid their dues.
So how would you catch malaria out of mines?
I don't know.
Those little holes, you know, had too much water in them, you know.
The mosquitoes were thick, you know.
Yeah, the mosquitoes.
Did you grow up at the mines, Cassidy?
We was all born out there but the baby sister.
1908, I see.
But you never went down in the mine?
Yeah, I went down.
Oh, you did?
We did too one time, we girls.
He just went with that, you know.
He had to go down there.
He used to look around.
He called it.
He used to go down there and look.
He'd survey down there, you know, surveyed with a compass and what you call those tapes, you know, with the numbers.
What do you call them?
Tape lines.
Tape lines.
And, you know, I'd help him sometimes, you know.
You know, carry the end of the tape line, you know, he'd measure the length, you know, and he'd write it down, you know.
You did that with your father?
Did you get paid for that?
Did you ever go down in the mine to work to get paid?
They loaded a box called one of these bricks, you know.
We had a brickyard out there, too.
And I decided to come out there.
There was about a half a brick right there.
It hit me right on the top of the head here.
It all bled.
It shot out.
I have a finger on that.
I went home, you know.
Did they make bricks?
Yeah, they had a brickyard, too.
Do you remember how they did that, how they made the bricks?
They had a press.
They had a press that pressed them.
Crested bricks, yeah.
How big was the kiln?
Eight foot size.
Right.
Did this clay come right along with the lignite?
No, I think they made the clay.
In the mines, there also is a white, they call it white clay.
They used some of it.
They made a clay pit on top of the ground, stripped the sand off, you know, and got that red clay and then that other below that.
Yeah, they'd make those fire clay.
They call it fire clay, that white clay.
They had a thing kind of like you see, those refrigerators they used to scrape with.
Kind of like a bulldozer.
Right.
They'd drag it along behind the mule.
But there's big drums that go around it.
There's wheels on there, you know.
And when they had it loaded, they'd make it where it'd come up, you know what I mean?
The load.
It closed up.
You know what I mean?
It'd rise there, and the mules would pull it out, you know.
I see.
And pull it to the press, you know.
The mules would pull it under the shed where they'd dump it.
Press the dump.
Lay in for it to go to the press.
Mm-hmm.
Well, did, once you all moved here, Gus, did you ever go back out to the mines?
Or did you pretty much forget about them once you left the mines?
No, I didn't go out there.
We'd go fishing.
It changed, though, it seemed like.
If we go out there now, it seemed like it changed a whole lot.
You know, it don't look like the right place, kind of.
Trees got big and, you know, and changed, you know, kind of.
Do you happen to remember the Texas Coal Company mine site at all?
Which one was the Texas Coal Company, Gus?
I don't think you know that.
What we're trying to do is to map that site.
They don't have maps of all the mines?
Well, we do have that, but we don't have an actual layout of the camps.
Oh.
And like where your house was and all the mines and where the commissary was and where all the little Mexican towns were.
Well, our house and grandmother's was on the hill like.
And it was kind of slanted down, you know what I mean?
Well, I tell you what, the Mexican really sat on the highway, you know, the Mexican houses.
We lived right across the river.
And it comes down, it comes down right at the Mexican houses there, right along in there somewhere.
I see.
Really across the river.
And then...
It was a little old store right beside our house, you know, in the camp, you know, in the camp.
They had three stores, I believe.
I believe the Texas mine was down there, Stripling's.
I mean, on the other side, the Texas mine was down there.
On the other side of our mine.
I call that our mine because that's grandmother's.
Well, that's close enough.
Yeah.
Do you remember anything else in mind, sir, when you were a little kid?
Did you play with the Mexican children?
No, pretty much.
Well, none of us ever played with the Mexicans.
See, like those days, it wasn't like now.
You know, they were separated.
Now, lots of the grown boys would play baseball with the Mexicans.
Yeah, yeah, play sometimes.
You had a big baseball field there, and they'd play baseball there.
Did you play baseball?
Sure.
What position did you play?
Oh, it was like the first base.
All right.
Not that far to run the dugout, is it?
Willie, did you play baseball?
I played some.
I never did like the back catch, you know.
It wasn't my play.
We girls played baseball, too, and we could play pretty good, too.
I tell you.
I was like the first baseman.
We went to Tower Ridge School, that's where we went to school.
Right across the railroad and you go over there, you see that Mexican camp out there?
You go straight up here, you know where Tower Ridge is at.
That's where we went to school.
All of us except, when we moved over here, then the babysitter was born over here, and she and Gus and several more of the other ones went over here too.
And after I was a young sister, I went to Roger's school after all, you know.
Three of them graduated.
I mean, Brother Ernest and Sister Claire and Emmer, they graduated up here at Roger's school.
I guess you were saying that it was pretty well separated between the Mexicans and the Anglicans.
Were there any blacks that worked at the mine?
At the brickyard.
It was funny that the niggers worked at the brickyard and the Mexicans, they worked at the mine.
Not a nigger working in the mine.
I don't know.
They wouldn't go down in there.
They hung around the brickyard at the nigger's wood.
You never did ask them why they wouldn't go down to the mine?
Was it more money at the brickyard?
No, I don't believe.
About the same?
They sprayed her just to go down there.
Well, I think I would be, too.
That is funny, you know, a human being.
You know, some places, they go down into the deep, you know, and you crawl way up from here to up by that nigger house up there, you know.
And all that dirt on top of you, what if that door falls?
Right, yeah.
I have it.
We did have two boiler explosions out back of mine.
One.
One, I mean, one.
Do you remember what year that was, Louise?
What year that boiler exploded?
That was 1900.
Must have been 10 or 12, huh?
No, it was late in that.
Because we had that other mine, the last mine was up there, that shell mine.
Do you remember that cave-in?
Uh-huh.
That mine where they were That was the same mine where they brought the exposed, where it caved in.
It's still there.
It's holding water now.
Is it?
Do you all remember that?
Did you go down to the cave-in?
Uh-huh.
Did you
We were going to school then, yeah.
And whenever it would rain a whole lot, you know, we had to walk to school.
And it was about three miles to school.
And we had to walk, carry our own lunch baskets and satchel full of books and things, you know.
We were loaded down.
Well, with that cave being in 1913, did you all go out there?
You would have been 13 years old, and Gus would have been five.
Did you go out there and help dig them out?
No, not me.
I didn't work there.
I wasn't old enough.
Do you remember that scene?
I was going to school, yeah.
And when it rained a whole lot, my mother would send one of the workers, the white men and all,
Send them with a wagon and a team and raincoats and umbrellas and things.
Send them to school after us kids.
And that's just when it happened.
We were all in school.
The time changed so much.
Those days, all we had was...
a pencil and a pen.
That's where we began, you know.
Right, you didn't have a fancy tape recorder.
And later on, when you get a little older, you have to have some ink and an ink pen, you know.
These days, look what you have to have these days to get it.
Right.
The school has changed.
Well, y'all went to your own school then.
You didn't go to school with the Mexicans?
No, no.
That was all separate.
Did you like going to the school guys?
Yeah, I liked it when I got older.
Yeah, Willie and I were talking a few moments ago.
Willie Holtzholdt.
Remember Willie Holtzholdt?
Holtzholdt, yeah, I'm sorry.
And he played hooky so much.
Yeah.
He'd go with us to where he kept halfway away.
There's a big place with woods on each side of the road, you know.
And he'd go to the van.
He'd say, all right, I'll see y'all this evening when y'all come back.
And he'd go in those woods and stay in there until we'd come back home from school.
And when we got there, he'd be there waiting for us.
And he'd walk home with us so nobody knew he didn't go to school, you know.
But I believe he had a sister go to school, and she's older.
And I think she told her daddy about him.
And her daddy gave him a good whipping.
Some mornings he had to take them to school halfway, you know.
to make them go.
Well, Gus, what do you think?
Don't tell him we told all of us.
Okay, I won't.
I won't tell him.
He may not have told you himself.
Yeah, he told me himself.
Don't like to be in the middle of it.
He talked about time, the one time at the store, and I said, at the city food market, I said, we used to go to school to get them.
He said, yes, Willie learned something, but I didn't.
I played hooky every day.
He said, Willie learned something, learned how to write and read.
I can't even write my own name, he said.
I told him.
Gus, what did you think when your older brother went down into the mines?
Do you remember that?
He don't remember.
He wasn't just old enough yet.
Do you remember how much you were getting paid back then when you were working in the mine?
I don't remember nothing now.
When you worked in the mine, you got paid by them little cars you filled.
I was wondering if you remembered how much it was per farm.
If you wouldn't fill but one, you wouldn't make much.
Right.
Some would be good diggers, and some wouldn't.
They'd come out of there early, and some would stay until...
They wouldn't work on the Saturday, just couldn't get no biscuits and work on the Saturday, just...
Well, they could get all the coal they wanted anyway, you know, usually.
They had to buy the mines ore, too, you know.
They wouldn't work on the city unless they'd get behind, you know, neat coal, extra, you know.
They had a switch running from the highway right there that's running out there now.
They had a switch from there on going out to the mines.
And every day...
When they had some cars loaded, they'd call it in, you know, out to town, and the trains, they had a special train.
They would come out to the mine?
They'd come out there and go out there and they'd switch and get those cars of coal out of there.
He'd bring the empties, you know, and take the fumes back to town.
He'd go to every mine, you know, out there the same day, you know, yeah.
Do you remember when the trucks came out to the mines?
Trucks.
Trucks.
Did they ever use trucks?
No, there wasn't no cars until...
I think my Uncle Herman had the first car.
That's Herman Vogel, right?
Uh-huh.
1915, I think, or 16.
That's when cars started coming in, you know.
And he had one, a beauty.
They went to town one night...
coming home and there was an old mule standing in the road.
He thought the mule would move and the mule, I guess, just stood there and he ran into him and the mule kicked and kicked the radiator, horn of the radiator.
So he had to get that fixed up.
Yeah, yeah.
He said, I slowed up but the mule wouldn't move, he said.
Well, do you know what's happened to the Mexican families?
There's some still living.
Yeah, I talked to a couple of them this morning.
I'm going to go back and we're going to do the same thing.
He talked to a real old lady out there.
A real old lady.
She might have moved to town by now.
Mr. Potter died here a month or two ago.
But she's got sons.
What do you mean?
Not that an old lady didn't die.
There's another old lady.
I forget what her name is.
But always come out and ask about Mama, that real old lady.
She didn't die.
They come out here?
Louise.
Uh-uh.
She didn't die because I talked to her before yesterday.
The other old lady died.
They come out.
We grow vegetables and sell them, you know.
Oh, you still do that?
Uh-uh.
Gus raises plants.
Some of them come out here and get plants.
These old Mexican women would come out here and buy plants.
And they're just, oh, they're just glad to see you.
They just shake hands and talk.
They were very friendly.
Ruth ordained them.
I lived in town and I'd meet up with one of those old Mexican men that worked in the mine.
He didn't know me.
He'd come there and shake hands with me and ask me how Mama was and how Papa was and how Mata was.
Asked her all about the family, you know.
They were real friendly.
If you ever get more mad at you, you just better look out.
He might as well stick you with a knife or something.
They was bad on you tonight when they get mad.
They use a knife more than a gun.
They take a knife.
You never had a run in, was it?
You never had a run in.
Do you think the lignite mining was good for Rockville?
Yeah, it helped.
Gave more work to do.
What do you think about Shell Oil coming in here now?
There'll be a lot more people coming in.
They're sure building up some new homes all around in Westwood and different places.
We went, I met you from down Baytown, because I feel anxious.
So I decided to build a dance hall, you know, a dance hall for the Mexicans, you know.
So they'd have some fun too, you know.
And he built a brand new one.
And the first dance, one of them was getting mad with the other that danced with his wife or something, you know.
And they started cutting up each other.
And Papa said, where are you?
If y'all want to do that, I just tag back down.
He tore it back down.
And that was Papa Lorraine?
No, that was Grandpa.
That was Grandpa.
He said, well, if y'all want to fight and kill each other, I just tag back down.
He tore it back down.
They said one day.
One day.
They had weddings out there, too.
And I tell you, when they have a wedding, they have a wedding.
They first get married by the Justice of the Peace.
Would the Justice of the Peace come out to the mining camp?
I guess if they wanted him to, but I believe they always went to town.
They'd get married at Justice of the Peace, and that night they'd have a big doing.
They'd dance, and...
They'd always invite Grandma Vogel and Mother and Daddy in if they wanted to go.
Did your parents, grandparents go to those weddings?
Yeah, I went too.
They took us older girls too along.
Did you have a good time?
Well, we just watched.
Just watched.
But they'd ask Mother and Grandma to dance if they wanted to dance.
And they'd let them dance first, you know, and then later on the others would dance.
And when Sunday morning would come, they'd all dress up and go to town, to church.
They'd get married again.
And some of the women would stay at home and they'd cook a big dinner, chicken and all kinds of, you know, big dinner.
And they'd cook them outside in boiling pots.
They'd cook out there in them, a big old dinner.
They'd bring, at their time, some they'd bring grandmother a plateful of food, and they'd bring us a plateful of food.
Wow.
That was nice.
Uh-huh.
They liked the guitar a whole lot.
They liked the guitar.
Did you ever learn how to play it?
No.
I never could learn.
We never did learn how to play anything.
Well, we wasn't able to take the music.
When they'd have their weddings sometimes, they'd leave and they'd have what you call game roosters, you know what I mean?
Five game roosters.
Oh, yeah, game roosters.
Yeah, and they, on Sundays, they'd always have a fight.
One would take it to the other house and do a lot of, you know, let's see what you can fight, you know, best, you know, win, you know.
So they'd raise their own cocks?
Yeah, yeah.
I see.
And sometimes they'd tell him, he had a .22, you know what I mean?
That little rifle.
Right.
They'd have a wedding.
They wanted to kill him when them roosters came by.
They couldn't catch him, you know?
So they'd tell him to come down there and he'd shoot him with that little rifle.
They'd give him a dollar for every one of his shoots, you know.
Did you watch any of the cock fights?
What?
Did you watch any?
No, I never watched any.
We never did mingle among them at all.
Do you remember where they came from?
Mexico.
How did your grandfather Vogel get a hold of them?
Sometimes they'd send some Mexicans from here to Mexico to get workers, you know, give them money enough to go down over there and get some, you know.
Your grandfather would trust them with the money to go down there?
I guess so.
He'd go down and get some and bring them back.
The only way they paid them first was after they got here.
I don't know what they've done now.
But they did work this thing.
They'd bring the whole family along.
In the summertime, during cotton picking season, you know, late summer and fall, the mines, they had to pay a little more, you know, to dig coal.
I remember some of them asking quick, you know,
Three or four kids, you know, they said they could make more money picking cotton, you know.
They had to, in the summer, pay a little more, raise the wages, you know.
So they started the mine.
Some of them had three or four kids, and they said they could make more money to take the kids, the whole family, picking cotton, you know.
Yet they had to give a little more during that sea of cotton-picking time.
They wouldn't all stay out there at one mine.
They'd change around.
They'd move out, go to another mine.
Why would they do that, Louise?
Sometimes they'd owe money.
They'd quickly leave out, you know, someone.
I see.
So another mind might pay more than your grandfather's mind.
Yeah, yeah.
It's like we do these days.
Yeah.
Somebody might pay you more if you go to work for the other man too.
It's the same way.
One day they go to work, you know, and there's like here, I guess you'd call it burglar, ain't it?
They took sledgehammer stuff and
Knocked all that brass off, you know, off the machinery, pipes and stuff.
They had to close down for about two days before they could go to work again.
You know what I mean?
Yeah, that happened at Jeremiah's?
At the brickyard, yeah.
At the brickyard, right.
Knocked that brass off, you know.
Did your grandpa have any labor problems?
Were there ever any strikes?
No.
I don't know.
We didn't even know what a strike was.
No, they didn't have no strikes.
They didn't have no trouble.
If the Mexican didn't like it, they'd just quit and leave, you know.
They'd get some more, you know.
They'd get some more.
Like I said, they'd sometimes need some workers, you know.
